Helper Functions¶

In [6]:
def tokenize(batch):
    '''This function applies tokenizer to a batch of examples; padding=True will pad the examples with
    zeros to the size of the longest one in a batch, and truncation=True will truncate the examples
    to the model's maximum context size.'''
    return tokenizer(batch["Claim Description"],padding=True, truncation = True)
In [7]:
def extract_hidden_states(batch):

    # Place model inputs on the GPU
    inputs = {k:v.to(device) for k,v in batch.items() if k in tokenizer.model_input_names}

    # Extract last hidden states
    with torch.no_grad():
        last_hidden_state = model(**inputs).last_hidden_state

    # Return vector for [CLS] token, and putting it back to CPU
    return {"hidden_state": last_hidden_state[:,0].cpu().numpy()}
In [8]:
def plot_confusion_matrix(y_preds,y_true, labels):
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_preds, normalize="true")
    fig,ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(20,6))
    disp = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix =cm, display_labels= labels)
    disp.plot(cmap="Blues", values_format=".2f", ax=ax, colorbar=False)
    plt.title("Normalized Confusion Matrix")
    plt.show()
In [9]:
def compute_metrics(pred):
    labels = pred.label_ids
    preds = pred.predictions.argmax(-1)
    f1 = f1_score(labels,preds,average="weighted")
    acc = accuracy_score(labels,preds)
    return {"accuracy":acc,"f1":f1}
In [10]:
def filter_high_frequency_classes(data,col,pct):
    # Get value counts for each category in 'Coverage Code'
    coverage_counts =data[col].value_counts(normalize=True)*100
    
    # Filter to retain only categories with counts greater than 1 pct
    high_frequency_class = coverage_counts[coverage_counts > pct].index
    
    return high_frequency_class
In [30]:
def label_int2str(x,label_mapping):
    label_mapping_rev={}
    for k,v in label_mapping.items():
        label_mapping_rev[v]=k
    return label_mapping_rev[x]

def str2int(x,label_mapping):

Only keeping high frequency categories and assigning rest to others¶

In [21]:
def assign_others(cat,high_frequency_cat):
    if cat in high_frequency_cat:
        return cat
    else:
        return 'other'
In [22]:

Maximum context size¶

  • Transformer models have a maximum input sequence length that is referred to as the maximum context size.
  • For applications using DistilBERT, the maximum context size is 512 tokens, which amounts to a few paragraphs of text.
In [45]:
df["Words Per review"] = df["Claim Description"].str.split().apply(len)
In [47]:
# Plotting the boxplot
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 6))
sns.boxplot(x='Coverage Code Merged', y='Words Per review', data=df)
plt.title('Boxplot of `Words Per review` by Category')
plt.xlabel('Category')
plt.ylabel('Value')
plt.show()
  • From the plot we see that for each emotion, most descriptions are around 15-40 words long and the longest descriptions are well below DistilBERT's maximum context size.
  • Texts that are longer than a model's context size needs to be truncated, which can lead to a loss in performance, if the truncated text contains crucial information.

Tokenization¶

  • Tokenzation is the step of breaking down a string into the atomic units used in the model.
  • Numericalization is the process of converting a character into an integer.
In [48]:
model_ckpt = "distilbert-base-uncased"
tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(model_ckpt)
  • The AutoTokenizer class belongs to a larger set of "auto" classes whose job is to automatically retrieve the model's configuration, pretrained weights, or vocabulary from the name of the checkpoint.

['[CLS]', 'the', 'o', '##v', 'made', 'a', 'left', 'turn', 'and', 'collided', 'with', 'the', 'iv', ',', 'that', 'was', 'attempting', 'to', 'pass', 'it', 'on', 'the', 'road', '.', 'the', 'iv', 'then', 'struck', 'a', 'wall', '.', 'the', 'iv', 'incurred', 'front', 'end', 'damage', '.', 'the', 'damage', 'to', 'the', 'o', '##v', 'is', 'unknown', 'and', 'the', 'wall', 'incurred', 'no', 'damage', '.', 'there', 'were', 'no', 'injuries', 'reported', '.', '[SEP]']
  • Observations:
    • [CLS], [SEP] are special tokens, denoting start and end of the sequence.
    • Tokens have been lowercased, which is a feature of this particular checkpoint.
    • Splitting of uncommon words.
      • The ## prefix in "##ez" and "##ure" means that the preceeding string is not whitespace; any token with this prefix should be merged with the previous token when you convert the tokens back to a string.

  • map() method operates individually on every example in the corpus, so setting batched=True will encode the tweets in batches.
  • batch_size=None will apply tokenize function on the full dataset as a single batch.
  • This ensures that input tensors and attention masks have the same shape globally.

Training a Text Classifier¶

In [56]:
Image(filename=r'C:\Users\abhij\Desktop\Transformers\transformers\Notebooks\Gallhagher_AJG\image2.png')
Out[56]:
  • Classification using DistilBERT:
    • First, the text is tokenized and represented as one-hot vectors called token encodings.
    • Second, token encodings are converted into token embeddings, which are vectors living in lower dimensional space.
    • Third, token embeddings are then passed through the encoder block layers to yield a hidden state for each input token.
    • Last step, for the pretraining objective of language modeling, hidden state is fed to a layer that predicts the masked input tokens.
      • For the classification task, we replace the language modeling layer with a classification layer
  • Options to train a model on a dataset:
    • Feature Extraction: Use the hidden states as features and just train a classifier on them, without modifying the pretrained model.
    • Fine-tuning: Train the whole model end-to-end, which also updates the parameters of the pretrained model.

Transformers as Feature Extractors¶

  • We freeze the body's weights during training and use the hidden states as features for the classifier.
  • This method is especially convenient if GPUs are unavailable, since the hidden states only need to be precomputed once.
In [57]:

  • AutoModel class converts the token encodings to embeddings, and then feeds them through the encoder stack to return the hidden states.

Visualizing the dataset¶

  • Since, visualizing the hidden states in 768 dimensions is tricky, we'll use the powerful UMAP algorithm to project the vectors down to 2D.
    • UMAP works best when the features are scaled to lie in the [0,1] interval.
In [66]:
X_train = np.array(description_hidden["hidden_state"])
y_train = np.array(description_hidden["label"])
X_valid = np.array(description_encoded_valid_hidden["hidden_state"])
y_valid = np.array(description_encoded_valid_hidden["label"])

print(X_train.shape, X_valid.shape)

(153170, 768) (38293, 768)
In [67]:
# Scale features to [0,1] range
X_scaled = MinMaxScaler().fit_transform(X_train[:20000])

# Initialize and fit UMAP
mapper = UMAP(n_components=2, metric = "cosine").fit(X_scaled)

# Create a DataFrame of 2D embeddings
df_emb = pd.DataFrame(mapper.embedding_, columns = ["X","Y"])
df_emb["label"]= y_train[:20000]

fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 6, figsize=(14, 8))  # Adjusted layout for 11 categories

# Iterate over each label and cmap

    df_emb_sub = df_emb.query(f"label == {label_code}")
    
    # Plotting hexbin for each category
    axes[i].hexbin(df_emb_sub["X"], df_emb_sub["Y"], cmap=cmap, gridsize=20, linewidths=(0,))
    axes[i].set_title(label_name)
    axes[i].set_xticks([])
    axes[i].set_yticks([])

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
  • These are only projections onto a lower-dimensional space. Just because some categories overlap does not mean that they are not separable in the original space. Conversely, if they are separable in the projected space they'll be separable in the original space.
  • Observations:
    • Both the categories appear to be separable.

You should probably TRAIN this model on a down-stream task to be able to use it for predictions and inference.

batch_size = 64

training_args = TrainingArguments(
    output_dir=model_name,
    num_train_epochs=10,
    learning_rate=2e-5,
    per_device_train_batch_size=batch_size,
    per_device_eval_batch_size=batch_size,
    weight_decay=0.01,
    evaluation_strategy="steps",
    save_steps=1000,
    save_strategy='steps', # we cannot set it to "no". Otherwise, the model cannot guess the best checkpoint.
    eval_steps=1000,
    disable_tqdm=False,
    logging_steps=logging_steps,
    log_level="error",
    report_to="none",
    load_best_model_at_end = True,
    save_total_limit=3,
    use_cpu=False,
    no_cuda=False
)
